        "header": "6Meet LingBot-Depth 2.0",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2607.05247/2607.05247v1/x1.png",
                "caption": "Figure 9:LingBot-Depth 2.0 on mirror and glass scenes.Each group shows the input RGB, the raw sensor depth\nand the refined depth for consecutive frames of a captured sequence,\ntogether with front and top views of the refined point cloud. The\nraw depth is missing exactly on the hardest surfaces: window panes,\na glass balustrade and reflective floors return no measurements.\nThe completed regions form flat, contiguous planes in the point\nclouds and remain stable over time.",
                "position": 2639
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2607.05247/2607.05247v1/x2.png",
                "caption": "Figure 10:Qualitative comparison of depth completion\nmethods.Each scene shows the completed depth map\n(top) and the corresponding point cloud (bottom) for OMNI-DC, CDMs,\nLingBot-Depth 1.0 and LingBot-Depth 2.0, next to the RGB frame with\nground-truth depth and the raw sensor input. The baselines leave\nmissing regions open, bend planar surfaces, or scatter floating\npoints near depth discontinuities; LingBot-Depth 2.0 keeps planes\nstraight and object boundaries sharp.",
                "position": 2649
            }
        ]
